         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>The style of the mosaic seems post-Hadrianic but earlier than the Byzantine reconstruction of the building.  
                It is perhaps evidence of a redecoration in the third or very early fourth century C.E.</p>
            <p>Or <foreign xml:lang="grc">
                  <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                  <unclear>εαλ</unclear>ις</foreign> or <foreign xml:lang="grc">
                  <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                  <unclear>σαλ</unclear>ις</foreign>. In the wall immediately above
                    the panel is a niche which contained, when excavated, the lower part of a statue of a woman accompanied 
                    by a winged creature - presumably Nemesis accompanied by a gryphon (see <bibl>
                  <author>Paribeni</author>, <title>Catalogo</title>, <citedRange>424</citedRange>
               </bibl>). 
                    It seems likely that the panel was relevant to the statue, and if, as is probable, the building was used for the 
                    administration of justice, the inscription might be suitably restored as <foreign xml:lang="grc">
                  <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                  <supplied reason="lost">θ</supplied>έμις</foreign>, 'Due Justice'. Otherwise the
                    letters are presumably from the end of a name, e.g. <foreign xml:lang="grc">Κερέαλις</foreign>, 'Cerealis'.
                </p>
         </div>
         
